<section id="TaskDesc">
<div class="page-header">
<h1>Task Description <small>What is this task all about?</small></h1>
</div>
This data collection task is part of our research project that aims to determine Citation Provenance (read more on the <a href="/about">purpose</a> of the project). The task, is to annotate scientific papers, capturing information leading to the information referred to by the citation (i.e. cited information).
<p>
<h2>Task Objective</h2>
<p>
The objective of this task is to gather manual annotations for our research. We wish to determine the classification of a citation, and the type of the citation. There is a total of <strong>12 classifications</strong>, and <strong>3 types</strong> of citation for our date collection. 
</p>
<div class="row">
	<div class="span6">
		<div class="alert alert-info">
			<h3>Classification</h3>
			<h4>Weak</h4>
				<code>Weak</code>
			<h4>Contrast or Comparison</h4>
				<code>CoCoGM</code>, <code>CoCoR0</code>, <code>CoCoR-</code>, <code>CoCoXY</code>
			<h4>Positive/Useful</h4>
				<code>PBas</code>, <code>PUse</code>, <code>PModi</code>, <code>PMot</code>, <code>PSim</code>, <code>PSup</code>
			<h4>Neutral</h4>
				<code>Neut</code>
		</div>	
	</div>
	<div class="span6">
		<div class="alert alert-success">
			<h3>Type</h3>
			<h4>General</h4>A <strong>General</strong> citation simply means Paper A is citing Paper B in general. Paper A is making reference to Paper B as a whole, or simply giving credit for the work done by authors of Paper B.
			<h4>Specific</h4>A <strong>Specific</strong> citation means Paper A is making reference to a <strong>specific</strong> section of Paper B. For instance, Paper A makes reference to a particular system, System ABC, created/described by Paper B in Paper B's second section (e.g. Our System). Since Paper A is specifically referring to this section of the paper, we say this cite is specific.
			<h4>Undetermined</h4>In cases where it is not possible to determine the type of the citation.
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<h2>Task Requirements</h2>
<p>
A participant, provided with a set of scientific papers, need to do the following:
<ul>
	<li>To determine the <strong>classification</strong> of the citation.</li>
	<li>To determine the <strong>type</strong> of the citation.</li>
	<li>To annotate the citation with the above details.</li>
</ul>
To do so, the participant needs to refer to the <strong>citing sentence</strong> in the citing paper, and attempt to locate the <strong>cited information</strong> in the cited paper. If you're ready, go on to <a href="./home#Annotate">How To Annotate</a>.
</p>
