<section id="Annotate">
<div class="page-header">
<h1>How To Annotate? <small>Let's get started!</small></h1>
</div>

<div class="row">
<div class="span8">
<p>
Recall that the objective of this task to determine the classification and type of the citation, and then to annotate with details about the citation. Annotating begins with a <strong>working file</strong> that will be provided to you. Your task, is to annotate by entering information into this working file. See that the <strong>first 3 lines</strong> has already been filled with the details. Don't worry about that dash / numbers / question mark means for now, we'll explain it shortly.
</p>
<h2>What do I need?</h2>
<p>To perform this task you would need:</p>
<ul>
<li>The <strong>working file</strong>, which tells you the citation relationship between papers. E.g. <code>A00-1003==>P99-1029</code> means <strong>A00-1003</strong> cites <strong>P99-1029</strong>.</li>
<li>A set of scientific papers (as referred to in the working file). Each file is named with its ID. E.g. <strong>A00-1001.txt</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>You would also need to use your favourite text editor that has <strong>line number display</strong>. <span class="muted">(I recommended <a href="http://www.sublimetext.com/2" target="_blank">Sublime Text 2</a>)</span></p>
</div>

<div class="span4">
<strong>Sample Working File</strong>
<pre class="prettyprint linenums">
A00-1003==>P99-1029,PSim,-
A00-1004==>A00-1019,CoCoGM,46!153-188
A00-1004==>J93-1006,Neut,?
A00-1004==>J93-2003,
A00-1004==>P91-1022,
A00-1004==>P91-1023,
</pre>
</div>
</div>

<h2>How do I <small>actually</small> annotate?</h2>
In the working file, we capture annotations in "3 columns" separated by the comma.
<div class="row">
<div class="span6">
<div class="alert alert-info">
<h3 align="center"><i>&lt;cite&gt;,&lt;classification&gt;,&lt;type&gt;</i></h3>
</div>
<p><strong>&lt;cite&gt;</strong> would be provided for you already. E.g. <code>A00-1003==>P99-1029</code></p>
<p><strong>&lt;classfication&gt;</strong> is one of the 12 classifications. E.g. <code>PSim</code></p>
<p><strong>&lt;type&gt;</strong> is one of the 3 types. E.g. <code>8!152-155</code></p>
<div class="alert alert-error">
<p>It is <strong>important</strong> that you know the explanations of classifications & types. Click <a href="/classification">here</a> to read more.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h2>Approach</h2>
<p>The approach to annotating one citation is as follow:</p>
<form class="well">
<ol>
<strong>Determining the Classification</strong>
<li>Is there any explicit weakness? Yes (Go to step 2) / No (Go to step 3)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>Weak</code>. (Go to step 21)</li>
<li>Is there any explicit statement that the author work is <strong>based</strong> on the cited paper? Yes (Go to step 4) / No (Go to step 5)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>PBas</code>. (Go to step 21)
<li>Is there any explicit statement about the author <strong>using</strong> any data/algorithms/definitions in the cited paper? Yes (Go to step 8) / No (Go to step 6)</li>
<li>Is there any explicit statement about the author <strong>adapts or modifies</strong> any data/algorithms in the cited paper? Yes (Go to step 8) / No (Go to step 7)</li>
<li>Is there any explicit statement about the author uses the cited paper as a <strong>motivation</strong>? Yes (Go to step 8) / No (Go to step 9)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>PUse</code> (from step 5) / <code>PModi</code> (from step 6) / <code>PMot</code> (from step 7). (Go to step 21)</li>
<li>Is there any explicit <strong>compare and contrast</strong> between the work in the citing paper and the cited paper? Yes (Go to step 10) / No (Go to step 13)</li>
<li>Is the compare and contrast <strong>negative</strong>? Yes (Go to step 11) / No (Go to step 12)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>CoCoR-</code>. (Go to step 21)</li>
<li>Is the compare and contrast is related to their <strong>goals and methods</strong>? Yes (Go to step 13) / No (Go to step 14)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>CoCoR0</code> (Go to step 21)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>CoCoGM</code>. (Go to step 21)</li>
<li>Is there any explicit statement about <strong>similarity</strong> with cited paper? Yes (Go to step 17) / No (Go to step 16)</li>
<li>Is there any explicit statement about the author <strong>supporting</strong> the cited paper? Yes (Go to step 17) / No (Go to step 18)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>PSim</code> (from step 15) / <code>PSup</code> (from step 16). (Go to step 21)</li>
<li>Is there any explicit statement about the author <strong>contrasting two works</strong> not related to the citing paper? Yes (Go to step 19) / No (Go to step 20)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>CoCoXY</code>. (Go to step 21)</li>
<li>Annotate as <code>Neut</code>. (Go to step 21)</li>

<strong>Determining the Type</strong>
<li>Can the type of citation determined? Yes (Go to step 23) / No (Go to step 22).
<li>Annotate as <code>?</code>(Represents Undetermined). (Go to step 26)
<li>Is the citation Specific? Yes (Go to step 25) / No (Go to step 24)
<li>Annotate as <code>-</code>(Represents General). (Go to step 26)
<li>Annotate as Specific(See #). Go to step 26.
<li>End.
</ol>
<p><i># Note:<br>
Recall the variations for Specific citations.<br>
For multi-locations, it can be a combination of single-line and multi-line i.e. <code>46!153-188</code> or <code>153-188!200</code><br>
If at this point you are unsure how to annotate Specific, check again <a href="/classification">here</a></i></p>
</form>
<h2>Getting Started</h2>
<p>The following is the general steps you need to take to complete this task:</p>
<form class="well">
<ol>
<li>Use your favourite text editor that has line number display. I recommend <a href="http://www.sublimetext.com/2" target="_blank">Sublime Text 2</a>.
<li>Open up the <strong>working file</strong>.
<li>Start from the first un-annotated entry you find.
<li>Open up the papers as identified by the IDs.
<li>In the cited paper, look for Author Names, Title, and Year of Publication. This gives you a clue how the citation would look like. With this info, look at the <strong>References</strong> section in the citing paper. Look for the citing sentence that contains the citation in the citing paper.
<li>Once you found the <strong>citing sentence</strong>, read briefly to find out that citation is for, and what cited information it is referring to.
<li>Now you know what the citation is for, look for the <strong>cited information</strong> in the cited paper. Then determine the <strong>classification & type</strong> of the citation.
<li>Annotate according to the <strong>Approach</strong>.
<li>Repeat step 3 till you are done.
</ol>
</form>
